# Architecture Overview

Theia is designed to work as a native desktop application as well as in the context of a browser and a remote server. To support both situations with a single source, Theia runs in two separate processes called frontend and backend respectively, which communicate through JSON-RPC messages over WebSockets or REST APIs over HTTP. In the case of Electron, both backend and frontend run locally, while in a remote context the backend would run on a remote host.

Both frontend and backend processes have their dependency injection (DI) container to which extensions can contribute.

## Frontend

The frontend process represents the client and renders the UI. In the browser, it simply runs in the rendering loop, while in Electron it runs in an Electron Window, which functions as a browser with additional Electron and Node.js APIs. Therefore, any frontend code may assume a browser as a platform but not Node.js.

The startup of the frontend process will first load the DI modules of all contributing extensions before obtaining an instance of `FrontendApplication` and calling `start()` on it.

## Backend

The backend process runs on Node.js. We use express as the HTTP server. It may not use any code that requires a browser (DOM API) as the platform.

The startup of the backend application will first load the DI modules of all contributing extensions before obtaining an instance of `BackendApplication` and calling `start(portNumber)` on it.

By default, the backend's express server also serves the code for the frontend.

## Separation By Platform

In an extension's top folder there is an additional layer of folders to separate by platform:

- The `common` folder contains code that doesn't depend on any runtime
- The `browser` folder contains code requiring a modern browser as a platform (DOM API)
- The `electron-browser` folder contains frontend code that requires DOM API as well as Electron renderer-process specific APIs
- The `node` folder contains backend code requiring Node.js as a platform
- The `node-electron` folder contains backend code specific for Electron

